column22: spear point - list says caribou eskimo, but MkPj is close to Bloody Falls and Copper Inuit, not Barrenlands Inuit.  Very finely made.  Tang and blade appear to be the same piece.  End of tang has a flattened and flaring section.  Edge of blade has obvious boundary of sharpening, roughly 3.75 mm wide on both edges.  there are several items in the CMH galleries that look like this but are made of slate.  They label them as 'flensing knives'.  the base of the antler handles on the slate display pieces has the small diamond projection that the base of the tang on this piece has.  I'm pretty sure this is actually a flensing knife

column8: soapstone vessel, incomplete, several parts repaired w. copper bands and sinew
column22: 15 existing copper staples.  They pretty much all take similar form.  Mend holes were drilled (?) into either side of the break in the soapstone, and the staples/bands were wrappede through to pull the pieces back together.  The amount of overlap of the ends of the staples seems to differ - some don't meet and some cross each other considerable.  In some cases there is a groove carved for the staple as well, so that it sits flush with the soapstone, but this is not always the case.  it looks like the ends of the staples are always to the interior of the vessel, and the middle section is always on the exterior.  It is hard to tell how the staples were made.  I think that at least some are hammered copper (as opposed to sheet).  3.87, 2.98, 4.67, 3.62, 4.68, 5.68 -  some of the widths.  1.11, 1.04, 1.55, 2.34 - some of the thicknesses.    there is variation in their size and shape, but all seem very regular in how they were made.
